The driver currently does not validate documents for insert or update:

{code}
$bulk = new MongoDB\Driver\BulkWrite;
$bulk->insert(['foo.bar' => 1]);
$bulk->insert(['x' => ['foo.bar' => 1]]);

$manager = new MongoDB\Driver\Manager(URI);
$manager->executeBulkWrite('test.foo', $bulk);
{code}

libmongoc's bulk write API does not validate documents for us. We will want to use the same logic (and validation flags) found in the relevant libmongoc collection methods.

The following segfaults for BSON encoding:

{code}
class MyIndirectlyRecursiveWrapper implements MongoDB\BSON\Serializable
{
    public $x => 1;

    public function bsonSerialize()
    {
        return ['x' => $this];
    }
}
{code}

The more direct example, where {{bsonSerialize()}} returns {{$this}}, is caught due to an earlier check that the return value is an array or stdClass.

On a related note, [bson-fromPHP-004.phpt|https://github.com/mongodb/mongo-php-driver/blob/1.2.8/tests/bson/bson-fromPHP-004.phpt] currently has tests for circular references in PHP arrays and generic objects, which result in the circular reference being ignored with no error. We should be throwing an exception instead of silently ignoring recursion.

